\begin_layout Section
Preferences under Risk and Uncertainity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a lot of uncertainity in markets.
 One of the things they enable us to do is to share uncertainity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Uncertainity has been around since the earliest days of the history.
 People were thinking of it in a way very similar to how they do it today.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There was no formal model of dealing with uncertainity until not a long
 time ago.
 The 
\series bold
expected utility maximization
\series default
 model has its roots in Pascal's Waget (1670), and became dominant with
 von-Meumann & Morgenstern (1947).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pascal addressed the notion of the expected outcome (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighed mean
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) in the question of what would be a fair end of a game.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expected utility can be represented in a decision matrix - consider
 an example with religion.
 The things we do not have control over (e.g 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

does god exist?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) are put in a columns, and the possible choices (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

whether to be a believer?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) are in rows of a table, which represents possible outcomes in terms of
 utility, with their respective probabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The St.
 Petersburg Paradox shows a situation where people are only willing to pay
 a low price for a game which has infinite expected yield in terms of value.
 Bernoulli solution: people do not maximize expect 
\series bold
value
\series default
, but only expected 
\series bold
utility
\series default
.
 As it is a 
\series bold
logarithimic
\series default
 function, it finally converges to a finite value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
People try to maximize the 
\series bold
expectation
\series default
 of the 
\series bold
utility
\series default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E[U(X)]=p_{1}u(x_{1})+p_{2}u(x_{2})+\cdots+p_{n}u(x_{n})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Betting - Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider starting with wealth given 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and being given a 
\begin_inset Formula $50\%$
\end_inset

 bet with 
\begin_inset Formula $+/-100$
\end_inset

 yield.
 It is a 
\series bold
fair
\series default
 bet, as 
\begin_inset Formula $E(X)=0$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $E(W+X)=W$
\end_inset

 (on average, nothing is lost or gained in the bet, compared to the current
 wealth).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximizing the expected 
\series bold
value
\series default
 maximization, one would be indifferent between taking or not taking the
 bet.
 But, attempting to maximize utility with a 
\series bold
concave
\series default
 utility function, we find out that the expected outcome of the bet is actually
 
\series bold
negative
\series default
, meaning that a risk averse person would be better off not taking the bet.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Eu(W+X)\leq u(W)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The uncertainty regarding the outcome in terms of wealth translates to an
 utility outcome uncertainity.
\end_layout

