\begin_layout Subsection
Insurance Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a car worth 100,000 which can be stolen with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

 and an insurance premium being 2000.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From expected 
\series bold
value
\series default
 maximization perspective, one shall not insure the car:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0.99\cdot100000+0.01\cdot0=99000>98000
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In real life there is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

moral hazard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem: if I buy the insurance, in some sense I'm not the one responsible
 for the car, thus I make decisions which put the insurance company at risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is very hard for the insurance company to assess that risk, thus usually
 a 
\series bold
