 The opposite is true as well: if 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0.6$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=0.5$
\end_inset

, one could sell them both for 
\begin_inset Formula $1.1$
\end_inset

 and make a sure gain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The no arbitrage theorem claims that in a perfect market, there are 
\series bold
