\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium in Financial Markets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider and example of agents with uncertain endowments.
 Will there be the equilibrium price? - Calculate by finding the net demand
 of each agent.
 Then make sure the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is such that they are equal (in a 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

- agents market, 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 need to clear).
 It can only work if 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Bot agents agree on the price (trying to smooth consumption).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The agents can also disagree and have equal endowments.
 But, because of different probabilities the slopes of the indifference
 curves are different - thus the initial point is not Pareto optimal.
 The equilibrium would be obtained at a price such that when adding up net
 demands, the result will be 0.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 will be the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

average belief
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

